   128â†’
   129â†’Sets `options.method` to the method name and makes a request.
   130â†’
   131â†’âŚ¨ď¸Ź **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional type parameter for use with JSON responses (see [`ky()`](#kyinput-options)).
   132â†’
  1052â†’### Sending form data
  1053â†’
  1054â†’Sending form data in Ky is identical to `fetch`. Just pass a [`FormData`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/FormData) instance to the `body` option. The `Content-Type` header will be automatically set to `multipart/form-data`, overriding any existing `Content-Type` header.
  1055â†’
  1056â†’```js
  1057â†’import ky from 'ky';
  1058â†’
  1059â†’// `multipart/form-data`
  1060â†’const formData = new FormData();
  1061â†’formData.append('food', 'fries');
  1062â†’formData.append('drink', 'icetea');
  1063â†’
  1064â†’const response = await ky.post(url, {body: formData});
  1065â†’```
  1066â†’
  1158â†’#### Native proxy support
  1159â†’
  1160â†’Node.js 24.5+ supports automatic proxy configuration via environment variables. Set `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1` or use the `--use-env-proxy` CLI flag.
  1161â†’
  1162â†’```sh
  1163â†’NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1 HTTP_PROXY=http://proxy.example.com:8080 node app.js
  1164â†’```
  1165â†’
  1166â†’Or:
  1167â†’
  1168â†’```sh
  1169â†’node --use-env-proxy app.js
  1170â†’```
  1171â†’
  1172â†’Supported environment variables:
  1294â†’#### How do I use this in Node.js?
  1295â†’
  1296â†’Node.js 18 and later supports `fetch` natively, so you can just use this package directly.
  1297â†’
